07584nam a22007815i 9780773559936DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2020438401  a97807735599367 a10.1515/97807735599362doi  a(DE-B1597)657933  a(OCoLC)1132424350  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aHX11.I5bL353 2019 4aInternet AccessbAGPC 7aHIS0370002bisacsh04a324.17500aLeft Transnationalism :bThe Communist International and the National, Colonial, and Racial Questions /ced. by Ian McKay, Oleksa Drachewych. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking Canada in the World ;v400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration and Sources -- tLeft Transnationalism? -- tOrientations -- t“Revolutionary Social Democracy” and the Third International -- tThe Russian Revolution, National Self-Determination, and Anti-Imperialism, 1917–1927 -- tOrigins of the Anti-Imperialist United Front -- tTransnationality in the Soviet Challenge to British India, 1917–1923 -- tTransnational Personal Relationships -- tLos poputchiki -- tThe Transnational Experience of Some Canadian Communists -- tBetween the Comintern, the Japanese Communist Party, and the Chinese Communist Party -- tRace and Colonialism -- tAnti-Colonialism and the Imperial Dynamic in the Anglophone Communist Movements in South Africa, Australia, and Britain -- tRace, the Comintern, and Communist Parties in British Dominions, 1920–1943 -- tThe Comintern and the Question of Race in the South American Andes -- tVarious Forms of Chineseness in the Origins of Southeast Asian Communism -- tNational Questions -- t“Young” and “Adult” Canadian Communists -- t“It Is Better to Retreat Now Than Be Crushed Altogether” -- tHenri Gagnon, Tim Buck, Stanley Ryerson, and the Contested Legacy of the Comintern on the National Question -- tNationalism and Internationalism in Chinese Communist Networks in the Americas -- tFuture Avenues for the Study of the Comintern and the National, Colonial, and Racial Questions -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1919, Bolshevik Russia and its followers formed the Communist International, also known as the Comintern, to oversee the global communist movement. From the very beginning, the Comintern committed itself to ending world imperialism, supporting colonial liberation, and promoting racial equality. Coinciding with the centenary of the Comintern's founding, Left Transnationalism highlights the different approaches interwar communists took in responding to these issues. Bringing together leading and emerging scholars on the Communist International, individual communist parties, and national and colonial questions, this collection moves beyond the hyperpoliticized scholarship of the Cold War era and re-energizes the field. Contributors focus on transnational diasporic and cultural networks, comparative studies of key debates on race and anti-colonialism, the internationalizing impulse of the movement, and the evolution of communist platforms through transnational exchange. Essays further emphasize the involvement of communist and socialist parties across Canada, Australia, India, China, Japan, Southeast Asia, Latin America, South Africa, and Europe. Highlighting the active discussions on nationality, race, and imperialism that took place in Comintern circles, Left Transnationalism demonstrates that this organization - as well as communism in general - was, especially in the years before 1935, far more heterogeneous, creative, and unpredictable than the rubber stamp of the Soviet Union described in conventional historiography. Contributors include Michel Beaulieu (Lakehead University), Marc Becker (Truman State University), Anna Belogurova (Freie Universitat Berlin), Oleksa Drachewych (University of Guelph), Daria Dyakonova (Université de Montréal), Alastair Kocho-Williams (Clarkson University), Andrée Lévesque (McGill University), Lars T. Lih (Independent Scholar), Ian McKay (McMaster University), Sandra Pujals (University of Puerto Rico), John Riddell (Ontario Institute of Studies in Education), Evan Smith (Flinders University), S.A. Smith (All Souls College, Oxford), Xiaofei Tu (Appalachian State University), and Kankan Xie (Peking University).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism. 0aImperialism. 0aRace relations. 0aTransnationalism. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aBeaulieu, Michel S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelogurova, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrachewych, Oleksa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrachewych, Oleksa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDyakonova, Daria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKocho-Williams, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLih, Lars T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLévesque, Andrée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKay, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKay, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPujals, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiddell, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca